            content:
                "# Oracle Query Optimization — Anti-Patterns & Fixes\n\n## Anti-Pattern Catalog\n\n### 1. Function on Indexed Column\n\n```sql\n-- ❌ BAD: Prevents index usage on last_name\nSELECT * FROM employees WHERE UPPER(last_name) = 'SMITH';\n\n-- ✅ FIX A: Function-based index\nCREATE INDEX idx_emp_upper_name ON employees(UPPER(last_name));\n\n-- ✅ FIX B: Virtual column + index\nALTER TABLE employees ADD (last_name_upper VARCHAR2(50) GENERATED ALWAYS AS (UPPER(last_name)) VIRTUAL);\nCREATE INDEX idx_emp_name_v ON employees(last_name_upper);\n\n-- ✅ FIX C: Store normalized\n-- Insert/update always stores UPPER; query on raw column\n```\n\n### 2. Implicit Type Conversion\n\n```sql\n-- ❌ BAD: order_id is NUMBER, comparing to string\nSELECT * FROM orders WHERE order_id = '12345';\n-- Oracle wraps: WHERE TO_NUMBER('12345') = order_id  (or worse, casts column)\n\n-- ✅ FIX: Use matching type\nSELECT * FROM orders WHERE order_id = 12345;\n```\n\n### 3. OR on Different Columns\n\n```sql\n-- ❌ BAD: Often causes full table scan\nSELECT * FROM employees WHERE department_id = 10 OR last_name = 'Smith';\n\n-- ✅ FIX: UNION ALL\nSELECT * FROM employees WHERE department_id = 10\nUNION ALL\nSELECT * FROM employees WHERE last_name = 'Smith' AND (department_id <> 10 OR department_id IS NULL);\n```\n\n### 4. SELECT * When Not Needed\n\n```sql\n-- ❌ BAD: Fetches all columns, may prevent index-only scan\nSELECT * FROM employees WHERE department_id = 10;\n\n-- ✅ FIX: Select only needed columns\nSELECT employee_id, first_name, last_name FROM employees WHERE department_id = 10;\n```\n\n### 5. NOT IN with NULLable Column\n\n```sql\n-- ❌ BAD: If subquery returns ANY NULL, entire NOT IN returns 0 rows\nSELECT * FROM employees WHERE dept_id NOT IN (SELECT dept_id FROM excluded);\n\n-- ✅ FIX: Use NOT EXISTS\nSELECT * FROM employees e\nWHERE NOT EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM excluded x WHERE x.dept_id = e.dept_id);\n```\n\n### 6. Correlated Subquery in SELECT (N+1)\n\n```sql\n-- ❌ BAD: Executes subquery per row\nSELECT e.employee_id,\n    (SELECT d.name FROM departments d WHERE d.id = e.dept_id) AS dept_name\nFROM employees e;\n\n-- ✅ FIX: Use JOIN\nSELECT e.employee_id, d.name AS dept_name\nFROM employees e LEFT JOIN departments d ON e.dept_id = d.id;\n```\n\n### 7. HAVING Instead of WHERE\n\n```sql\n-- ❌ BAD: Filters AFTER grouping (processes all rows first)\nSELECT dept_id, COUNT(*) FROM employees GROUP BY dept_id HAVING dept_id = 10;\n\n-- ✅ FIX: Filter BEFORE grouping\nSELECT dept_id, COUNT(*) FROM employees WHERE dept_id = 10 GROUP BY dept_id;\n```\n\n### 8. DISTINCT to Mask Bad Joins\n\n```sql\n-- ❌ BAD: DISTINCT hides duplicate issue\nSELECT DISTINCT e.employee_id, e.first_name FROM employees e\nJOIN departments d ON e.department_id = d.department_id;\n\n-- ✅ FIX: Fix the join; if 1:1, DISTINCT is unnecessary\n```\n\n### 9. Leading Wildcard LIKE\n\n```sql\n-- ❌ BAD: Cannot use B-tree index\nSELECT * FROM employees WHERE last_name LIKE '%mith';\n\n-- ✅ FIX: Oracle Text index\nCREATE INDEX idx_emp_text ON employees(last_name) INDEXTYPE IS CTXSYS.CONTEXT;\nSELECT * FROM employees WHERE CONTAINS(last_name, '%mith') > 0;\n```\n\n### 10. Literal SQL Instead of Bind Variables\n\n```sql\n-- ❌ BAD: Each value generates a new hard parse\nSELECT * FROM employees WHERE employee_id = 42;\nSELECT * FROM employees WHERE employee_id = 43; -- different plan entry\n\n-- ✅ FIX: Use bind variables\nSELECT * FROM employees WHERE employee_id = :id;\n```\n\n### 11. UNION Instead of UNION ALL\n\n```sql\n-- ❌ BAD: UNION sorts and deduplicates — expensive\nSELECT id FROM table_a UNION SELECT id FROM table_b;\n\n-- ✅ FIX: Use UNION ALL if duplicates are OK or impossible\nSELECT id FROM table_a UNION ALL SELECT id FROM table_b;\n```\n\n### 12. COUNT(*) for Existence Check\n\n```sql\n-- ❌ BAD: Scans all matching rows just to check existence\nSELECT COUNT(*) INTO v_count FROM orders WHERE customer_id = :id;\nIF v_count > 0 THEN ...\n\n-- ✅ FIX: EXISTS stops at first row\nSELECT CASE WHEN EXISTS (SELECT 1 FROM orders WHERE customer_id = :id)\n    THEN 1 ELSE 0 END INTO v_exists FROM DUAL;\n```\n\n### 13. Row-by-Row Processing (Slow-by-Slow)\n\n```sql\n-- ❌ BAD: Cursor loop with single-row DML\nFOR rec IN (SELECT * FROM employees) LOOP\n    UPDATE employees SET salary = rec.salary * 1.1 WHERE employee_id = rec.employee_id;\nEND LOOP;\n\n-- ✅ FIX A: Single SQL (best)\nUPDATE employees SET salary = salary * 1.1;\n\n-- ✅ FIX B: BULK COLLECT + FORALL (if procedural logic needed)\nSELECT employee_id BULK COLLECT INTO v_ids FROM employees;\nFORALL i IN 1..v_ids.COUNT\n    UPDATE employees SET salary = salary * 1.1 WHERE employee_id = v_ids(i);\n```\n\n### 14. Missing Foreign Key Indexes\n\n```sql\n-- ❌ BAD: FK column without index causes table-level lock on parent DML\nALTER TABLE orders ADD CONSTRAINT fk_ord_cust\n    FOREIGN KEY (customer_id) REFERENCES customers(customer_id);\n-- No index on orders.customer_id!\n\n-- ✅ FIX: Always index FK columns\nCREATE INDEX idx_orders_cust ON orders(customer_id);\n```\n\n### 15. Wrong Pagination Pattern (Pre-12c)\n\n```sql\n-- ❌ BAD: ROWNUM applied before ORDER BY\nSELECT * FROM employees WHERE ROWNUM <= 10 ORDER BY salary DESC;\n\n-- ✅ FIX (Pre-12c): Subquery first\nSELECT * FROM (SELECT * FROM employees ORDER BY salary DESC) WHERE ROWNUM <= 10;\n\n-- ✅ FIX (12c+): Row Limiting\nSELECT * FROM employees ORDER BY salary DESC FETCH FIRST 10 ROWS ONLY;\n```\n\n---\n\n## Execution Plan Red Flags\n\n| Operation | Concern | Action |\n|---|---|---|\n| `TABLE ACCESS FULL` on large table | Missing index or unusable predicate | Check WHERE clause; add index |\n| `FILTER` | Row-by-row subquery execution | Rewrite as JOIN or use `EXISTS` |\n| `SORT ORDER BY` with high TEMP usage | Sorting spills to disk | Add index matching ORDER BY; reduce result set |\n| `NESTED LOOPS` with large driving set | Should be HASH JOIN | Check statistics; consider hint `USE_HASH` |\n| `HASH JOIN` for tiny lookup table | Should be NESTED LOOPS | Check statistics; consider hint `USE_NL` |\n| Very high `CONSISTENT GETS` | Reading too many buffers | Query returns too many rows or wrong index |\n| `CARTESIAN MERGE JOIN` | Missing join condition! | Fix the query — accidental cross join |\n\n---\n\n## Statistics Management\n\n```sql\n-- Gather table stats (MUST do after large data changes)\nEXEC DBMS_STATS.GATHER_TABLE_STATS('SCHEMA', 'TABLE', CASCADE => TRUE);\n\n-- Gather schema stats\nEXEC DBMS_STATS.GATHER_SCHEMA_STATS('SCHEMA');\n\n-- Check stale stats\nSELECT table_name, num_rows, last_analyzed, stale_stats\nFROM user_tab_statistics WHERE stale_stats = 'YES';\n\n-- Extended stats for correlated columns\nSELECT DBMS_STATS.CREATE_EXTENDED_STATS('HR', 'ADDRESSES', '(city, state)') FROM DUAL;\n```\n",
